<tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Lemma"><frontmatter> <anchor>15466</anchor> <addr>jms-004N</addr>  <route>jms-004N.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Linear and thunkable inverses</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> be a deductive system, and let <tex>f : A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. Then both the type of (linear, thunkable) <link href="jms-004O.xml" type="local">inverses</link> of <tex>f</tex> is a proposition.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15468</anchor> <addr>jms-004U</addr>  <route>jms-004U.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses and invertibility in deductive systems</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Inverses to morphisms in a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local">deductive system</link> need not be unique due to the general failure of associativity; therefore, we must be careful when speaking of “invertible maps” or “isomorphisms”. It happens that both linear and thunkable inverses <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">are unique</link>.</p><tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="false" toc="true" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>1</crumb></trail> <anchor>15470</anchor> <addr>jms-004O</addr>  <route>jms-004O.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses in a deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f : A  \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. An <em>inverse</em> to <tex>f</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>g : B \vdash  A</tex> such that <tex>f;g =  1 _{ A }</tex> and <tex>g;f =  1 _{ B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="false" toc="true" root="false" taxon="Lemma"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>2</crumb></trail> <anchor>15472</anchor> <addr>jms-004N</addr>  <route>jms-004N.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Linear and thunkable inverses</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> be a deductive system, and let <tex>f : A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. Then both the type of (linear, thunkable) <link href="jms-004O.xml" type="local">inverses</link> of <tex>f</tex> is a proposition.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="false" toc="true" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>15474</anchor> <addr>jms-004R</addr>  <route>jms-004R.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Thunkably and linearly invertible maps</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f:A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. We say that <tex>f</tex> is <em>(thunkably, linearly) invertible</em> when there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">(thunkable, linear) inverse</link> to <tex>f</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>15476</anchor> <addr>jms-004O</addr>  <route>jms-004O.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses in a deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f : A  \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. An <em>inverse</em> to <tex>f</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>g : B \vdash  A</tex> such that <tex>f;g =  1 _{ A }</tex> and <tex>g;f =  1 _{ B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>15478</anchor> <addr>jms-004P</addr>  <route>jms-004P.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Downshift structure</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> be a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local">deductive system</link> and let <tex>A</tex> be an object of <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. A <em>downshift structure</em> for <tex>A</tex> is defined to be a
  <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local">positive</link> object <tex>\mathord{\Downarrow}   A</tex> and a <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local">thunkable</link> map <tex>\mathsf{wrap} _{ A }  : A \vdash \mathord{\Downarrow}   A</tex> for which there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">necessarily unique and linear</link> inverse <tex>\mathsf{unwrap} _{ A }  :  \mathord{\Downarrow}   A \vdash  A</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15480</anchor> <addr>jms-004U</addr>  <route>jms-004U.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses and invertibility in deductive systems</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Inverses to morphisms in a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local">deductive system</link> need not be unique due to the general failure of associativity; therefore, we must be careful when speaking of “invertible maps” or “isomorphisms”. It happens that both linear and thunkable inverses <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">are unique</link>.</p><tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="false" toc="true" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>4</crumb></trail> <anchor>15482</anchor> <addr>jms-004O</addr>  <route>jms-004O.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Inverses in a deductive system</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f : A  \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. An <em>inverse</em> to <tex>f</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>g : B \vdash  A</tex> such that <tex>f;g =  1 _{ A }</tex> and <tex>g;f =  1 _{ B }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="false" toc="true" root="false" taxon="Lemma"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>5</crumb></trail> <anchor>15484</anchor> <addr>jms-004N</addr>  <route>jms-004N.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Linear and thunkable inverses</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> be a deductive system, and let <tex>f : A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. Then both the type of (linear, thunkable) <link href="jms-004O.xml" type="local">inverses</link> of <tex>f</tex> is a proposition.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show_heading="true" show_metadata="false" toc="true" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter><trail><crumb>6</crumb></trail> <anchor>15486</anchor> <addr>jms-004R</addr>  <route>jms-004R.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Thunkably and linearly invertible maps</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f:A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. We say that <tex>f</tex> is <em>(thunkably, linearly) invertible</em> when there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">(thunkable, linear) inverse</link> to <tex>f</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>15488</anchor> <addr>jms-004R</addr>  <route>jms-004R.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Thunkably and linearly invertible maps</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>f:A \vdash  B</tex> be a morphism in a deductive system <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. We say that <tex>f</tex> is <em>(thunkably, linearly) invertible</em> when there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">(thunkable, linear) inverse</link> to <tex>f</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show_heading="true" show_metadata="true" toc="false" root="false" taxon="Definition"><frontmatter> <anchor>15490</anchor> <addr>jms-004M</addr>  <route>jms-004M.xml</route> <date>April 15, 2023</date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Upshift structure</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex> be a <link href="jms-0048.xml" type="local">deductive system</link> and let <tex>A</tex> be an object of <tex>\mathcal{D}</tex>. An <em>upshift structure</em> for <tex>A</tex> is defined to be a
  <link href="jms-004B.xml" type="local">negative</link> object <tex>\mathord{\Uparrow}   A</tex> and a <link href="jms-004A.xml" type="local">linear</link> map <tex>\mathsf{force} _{ A }  :  \mathord{\Uparrow}   A \vdash  A</tex> for which there exists a <link href="jms-004N.xml" type="local">necessarily unique and thunkable</link> inverse <tex>\mathsf{delay} _{ A }  : A \vdash   \mathord{\Uparrow}   A</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>